					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td colspan=2 valign=bottom style=width:13.84%;border-top:2pt double #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;33.7
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.88%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td colspan=2 valign=bottom style=width:13.84%;border-top:2pt double #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;36.2
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.14%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Income Taxes&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We account for income taxes under the asset and liability method
 which requires the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Under this method
 deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the differences between the financial statements and tax basis of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The effect of a change in tax rates on deferred tax assets and liabilities is recognized in income in the period that includes the enactment date.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We record net deferred tax assets to the extent we believe these assets will more likely than not be realized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In making such determination
 we consider all available positive and negative evidence
 including future reversals of existing taxable temporary differences
 projected future taxable income
 tax planning strategies and recent financial operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Failure to achieve forecasted taxable income in applicable tax jurisdictions could affect the ultimate realization of deferred tax assets and could result in an increase in our effective tax rate on future earnings.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;A valuation allowance is provided when it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The Company uses a two-step approach to recognize and measure uncertain tax positions.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The first step is to evaluate the tax position for recognition by determining if the weight of available evidence indicates that it is more likely than not that the position will be sustained on audit
 including resolutions of related appeals or litigation processes
 if any.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The second step is to measure the tax benefit as the largest amount that is more likely than not of being realized upon ultimate settlement.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company believes that its income tax filing positions and deductions would be sustained upon examination; thus
 the Company has not recorded any uncertain tax positions as of December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;It is our policy to recognize interest and penalties accrued on any unrecognized tax benefits as a component of income tax expense.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We do not have any accrued interest or penalties associated with unrecognized tax benefits for the years ended December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We file income tax returns in the U.S. federal jurisdiction and various state jurisdictions.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The material jurisdictions that are subject to examination by tax authorities include the U.S. federal
 Arizona
 California and Indiana.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our U.S. federal income tax returns for years 2011 through 2013 remain open to examination by the Internal Revenue Service.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our state tax returns for years 2010 through 2013 remain open to examination by the state jurisdictions.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;5.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;;font-size: 10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;padding:0pt 36pt 0pt 0pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:3pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;Inventories&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Inventories consisted of the following as of December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013 (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:55.08%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:03.74%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td colspan=2 valign=bottom style=width:18.00%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;&gt;December&amp;nbsp;27
&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;&gt;2014&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:03.74%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td colspan=2 valign=bottom style=width:18.00%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;

&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;&gt;2013&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.46%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;

				&lt;/td&gt;

				&lt;/td&gt;

651&amp;nbsp;
				&lt;/td&gt;

216&amp;nbsp;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:03.74%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;

				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.94%;border-top:1pt solid #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;

				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:16.06%;border-top:1pt solid #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;43
086&amp;nbsp;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.46%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;

		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Inventories&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Inventories are stated at the lower of cost (first-in
 first-out) or market.&amp;nbsp; We identify slow moving or obsolete inventories and estimate appropriate write-down provisions related thereto.&amp;nbsp; If actual market conditions are less favorable than those projected by management
 additional inventory write downs may be required.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In the ordinary course of business
 we manage price and supply risk of commodities by entering into various short-term purchase arrangements with our vendors.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt; padding-right:0.5pt;&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;12.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt; padding-right:4pt;text-align:left&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Legal Proceedings&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We are periodically a party to various lawsuits arising in the ordinary course of business.&amp;nbsp; Management believes
 based on discussions with legal counsel
 that the resolution of any such lawsuits
 individually and in the aggregate
&amp;nbsp;will not have a material adverse effect on our financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Under our license agreement with the Jamba Juice Company (&amp;#x201C;Jamba Juice&amp;#x201D;)
 we are obligated and have agreed to indemnify and defend Jamba Juice in the two matters identified below
 and Jamba Juice has tendered defense of these matters to us.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In March&amp;nbsp;2012
 we learned that Jamba Juice was named as a defendant in a putative class action filed in the Federal Court for the North District of California and captioned &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Anderson v. Jamba Juice Company&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; (the &amp;#x201C;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Anderson&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; Matter&amp;#x201D;).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The plaintiff purports to represent a class of individuals who purchased make-at-home smoothie kits from Jamba Juice
 and alleges that such smoothie kits contain unnaturally processed
 synthetic and/or non-natural ingredients and that use of the words &amp;#x201C;All Natural&amp;#x201D; on the labels of these smoothie kits is unfair and fraudulent and violates various false advertising and unfair competition laws.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Anderson&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; Matter is one of several &amp;#x201C;all natural&amp;#x201D; lawsuits recently brought against various food manufacturers and distributors in California.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In an amended complaint
 the plaintiff also alleged violations of the federal Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act
 which were dismissed by the court in August&amp;nbsp;2012.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In a second amended complaint filed in September&amp;nbsp;2012
 we were added as a defendant.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Pursuant to the parties&amp;#x2019; stipulation
 on September&amp;nbsp;3
 2013 the court dismissed the &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Anderson&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; Matter.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;On June&amp;nbsp;28
 2013
 a class action complaint against Jamba Juice and the Company
 captioned&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt; Lilly v. Jamba Juice Company et al&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; (the &amp;#x201C;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Lilly&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; Matter&amp;#x201D;)
 was filed in the Federal Court for the Northern District of California
 with nearly identical allegations as those made in the Anderson Matter
 except that the complaint also alleges that the smoothie kits contain two additional allegedly non-natural ingredients.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The plaintiffs in this new action are represented by the same counsel that represented the plaintiff in the &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Anderson&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; Matter.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;While we currently believe the &amp;#x201C;all natural&amp;#x201D; statement on the smoothie kits are not misleading and in full compliance with FDA guidelines
 we are investigating the claims asserted in the &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Lilly&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; Matter
 and intend to vigorously defend against them.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;On September&amp;nbsp;17
 2013
 we filed a motion to dismiss
 seeking to dismiss plaintiffs&amp;#x2019; claims as to gelatin and the Orange Dream Machine smoothie kit.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our motion was denied in November&amp;nbsp;2013.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;On February&amp;nbsp;3
 2014
 the plaintiffs filed a motion to certify a class of all persons in California who bought certain Jamba Juice smoothie kits.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;On September&amp;nbsp;18
 2014
 the court issued an order granting class certification solely for purposes of determining liability and denying certification for purposes of damages.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The court requested further briefing on the question of whether it has jurisdiction to certify a class for purposes of granting injunctive relief.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Following mediation
 the basic terms of a proposed class settlement were reached.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The parties signed a definitive agreement that was filed with the court for approval on December 1
 2014.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The court&amp;#x2019;s ruling on a motion for preliminary approval is pending and will be followed by a subsequent final approval hearing.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If approved by the court
 a settlement class will be certified for injunctive relief only
 requiring the Company to (i) remove the &amp;#x201C;all natural&amp;#x201D; designation on the labels of the challenged products and (ii) pay $5
000 to each of the two individual plaintiffs and up to $425
000 to plaintiffs&amp;#x2019; counsel for fees and costs. The case would also be dismissed and the Company would pay no damages to class members
 althought there would be no release by class members of any individual damage claims they might have related to the Lilly Matter.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;On February&amp;nbsp;13
 2014
 the Company was sued in two putative class actions filed by Vanessa Montantes alleging that it recorded telephone calls made to its consumer affairs telephone number without obtaining consent to recording as allegedly required by California law.&amp;nbsp; One of the actions was filed in California State Court and captioned Vanessa Montantes v. Inventure Foods
&amp;nbsp;Inc. doing business as Boulder Canyon Natural Foods
 Superior Court for the State of California for the County of Los Angeles Case No.&amp;nbsp;BC536218.&amp;nbsp; This state court action was dismissed by the plaintiff within a few days of its original filing date.&amp;nbsp; The other action was filed in Federal Court and captioned Vanessa Montantes v. Inventure Foods d/b/a Boulder Canyon Natural Foods
 United States District Court for the Central District of California Case No.&amp;nbsp;CV14-1128 MWF (RZx).&amp;nbsp; The Company filed a motion to dismiss the complaint on April&amp;nbsp;21
 2014
 which was denied on June&amp;nbsp;9
 2014.&amp;nbsp; The Company also demanded indemnity from EMS
&amp;nbsp;Inc.
 the independent contractor that answered the consumer affairs calls
 but EMS
&amp;nbsp;Inc. has not agreed to indemnify the Company.&amp;nbsp; On July&amp;nbsp;15
 2014
 plaintiff filed a First Amended Complaint adding EMS
&amp;nbsp;Inc. as a defendant.&amp;nbsp; The Company answered the First Amended Complaint on August&amp;nbsp;1
 2014.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;On January 7
 2015
 the federal action was dismissed with prejudice pursuant to the stipulation of the parties.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;On February 26
 2015
 the Company received a demand letter from counsel in California purporting to represent plaintiff
 Maria Ghermezian and other California consumers.&amp;nbsp; The letter alleges that the Company&amp;#x2019;s use of the words &amp;#x201C;all natural&amp;#x201D; to describe certain kettle cooked potato chips is misleading and deceptive to consumers and violates the California Consumer Legal Remedies Act.&amp;nbsp; The demand letter seeks changes to the Company&amp;#x2019;s advertising of the products
 a recall of the products
 and restitution.&amp;nbsp; Numerous &amp;#x201C;all natural&amp;#x201D; lawsuits have been brought against various food manufacturers and distributors in California over the past several years
 including the Company.&amp;nbsp; While we currently believe the &amp;#x201C;all natural&amp;#x201D; claims on certain of our potato chip packages are not misleading
 we are investigating the claims asserted in the letter
 and intend to vigorously defend against them.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Recent Accounting Pronouncements&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Changes to U.S. GAAP are established by the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&amp;#x201C;FASB&amp;#x201D;) in the form of accounting standards updates (&amp;#x201C;ASU&amp;#x201D;) to the FASB&amp;#x2019;s Accounting Standards Codification.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We consider the applicability and impact of all ASUs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;ASUs not listed below were assessed and determined to be either not applicable or are expected to have minimal impact on our consolidated financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In 2013
 the FASB issued accounting guidance on the financial statement presentation of an unrecognized tax benefit when a net operating loss carryforward
 a similar tax loss or a tax credit carryforward exists.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The guidance is effective prospectively for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those years
 beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2013.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The implementation of the guidance did not have a material impact on our consolidated financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In April&amp;nbsp;2014
 the FASB issued amendments to guidance for reporting discontinued operations and disposals of components of an entity.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The amended guidance requires that a disposal representing a strategic shift that has (or will have) a major effect on an entity&amp;#x2019;s financial results or a business activity classified as held for sale should be reported as discontinued operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The amendments also expand the disclosure requirements for discontinued operations and add new disclosures for individually significant dispositions that do not qualify as discontinued operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The amendments are effective prospectively for fiscal years
 and interim reporting periods within those years
 beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2014 (early adoption is permitted only for disposals that have not been previously reported).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The implementation of the amended guidance is not expected to have a material impact on our consolidated financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In May&amp;nbsp;2014
 the FASB issued new accounting guidance related to revenue recognition.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This new standard will replace all current U.S. GAAP guidance on this topic and eliminate all industry-specific guidance.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The new revenue recognition standard provides a unified model to determine when and how revenue is recognized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The core principle is that a company should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration for which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This guidance will be effective at the beginning of our 2017 fiscal year and can be applied either retrospectively to each period presented or as a cumulative-effect adjustment as of the date of adoption.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We are evaluating the impact
 if any
 of adopting this new accounting standard on our financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In June&amp;nbsp;2014
 the FASB issued new guidance related to stock compensation.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The new standard requires that a performance target that affects vesting
 and that could be achieved after the requisite service period
 be treated as a performance condition.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As such
 the performance target should not be reflected in estimating the grant date fair value of the award.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This update further clarifies that compensation cost should be recognized in the period in which it becomes probable that the performance target will be achieved and should represent the compensation cost attributable to the periods for which the requisite service has already been rendered.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The new standard is effective for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those fiscal years
 beginning after December&amp;nbsp;15
 2015 and can be applied either prospectively or retrospectively to all awards outstanding as of the beginning of the earliest annual period presented as an adjustment to opening retained earnings.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Early adoption is permitted.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We are evaluating the impact
 if any
 of adopting this new accounting guidance on our financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;1.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Operations and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Description of Business&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Inventure Foods
&amp;nbsp;Inc.
 a Delaware corporation (referred to herein as the &amp;#x201C;Company
&amp;#x201D; referred to as &amp;#x201C;we
&amp;#x201D; &amp;#x201C;our&amp;#x201D; or &amp;#x201C;us&amp;#x201D;)
 is a leading marketer and manufacturer of healthy/natural and indulgent specialty snack food brands with more than $285 million in annual net revenues for fiscal year 2014.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We specialize in two primary product categories: (1)&amp;nbsp;healthy/natural food products and (2)&amp;nbsp;indulgent specialty snack products.&amp;nbsp; We sell our products nationally through a number of channels including: grocery
 natural
 mass merchandisers
 drug
 club
 value
 vending
 food service
 convenience stores and international.&amp;nbsp; Our goal is to have a diversified portfolio of brands
 products
 customers and distribution channels.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In our healthy natural food category
 products include Rader Farms&amp;#xAE; frozen berries
 Boulder Canyon&amp;#xAE; brand kettle cooked potato chips
 Willamette Valley Fruit Company&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:6.5pt;&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; brand frozen berries
 Fresh Frozen&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:6.5pt;&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt; brand frozen vegetables
 Jamba&amp;#xAE; branded blend-and-serve smoothie kits under license from Jamba Juice Company
 Seattle&amp;#x2019;s Best Coffee&amp;#xAE; Frozen Coffee Blends branded blend-and-serve frozen coffee beverage under license from Seattle&amp;#x2019;s Best Coffee
 LLC and private label frozen fruit and healthy/natural snacks.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;In our indulgent specialty snack food category
 products include T.G.I. Friday&amp;#x2019;s&amp;#xAE; brand snacks under license from T.G.I. Friday&amp;#x2019;s Inc. (&amp;#x201C;T.G.I. Friday&amp;#x2019;s&amp;#x201D;)
 Nathan&amp;#x2019;s Famous&amp;#xAE; brand snack products under license from Nathan&amp;#x2019;s Famous Corporation
 Vidalia&amp;#xAE; brand snack products under license from Vidalia Brands
&amp;nbsp;Inc.
 Poore Brothers&amp;#xAE; kettle cooked potato chips
 Bob&amp;#x2019;s Texas Style&amp;#xAE; kettle cooked chips
 and Tato Skins&amp;#xAE; brand potato snacks.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We also manufacture private label snacks for certain grocery retail chains and co-pack products for other snack and cereal manufacturers.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We operate in two segments: frozen products and snack products.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The frozen products segment includes frozen fruits
 vegetables and beverages for sale primarily to groceries
 club stores and mass merchandisers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;All products sold under our frozen products segment are considered part of the healthy/natural food category.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The snack products segment includes potato chips
 kettle chips
 potato crisps
 potato skins
 pellet snacks
 sheeted dough products
 cereal and extruded products for sale primarily to snack food distributors and retailers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The products sold under our snack products segment includes products considered part of the indulgent specialty snack food category
 as well as products considered part of the healthy/natural food category.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We operate manufacturing facilities in eight locations.&amp;nbsp; Our frozen berry products are processed in Lynden
 Washington
 Salem
 Oregon and Jefferson
 Georgia.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our frozen berry business grows
 processes and markets premium berry blends
 raspberries
 blueberries and rhubarb and purchases blackberries
 cherries
 cranberries
 strawberries and other fruits from a select network of fruit growers for resale.&amp;nbsp; The fruit is processed
 frozen and packaged for sale and distribution to wholesale customers.&amp;nbsp; Our frozen vegetable products are processed in Jefferson
 Georgia
 Thomasville
 Georgia and in Salem
 Oregon.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our frozen beverage products are packaged at our Lynden
 Washington and Jefferson
 Georgia facilities.&amp;nbsp; We also use third-party processors for certain frozen products and package certain frozen fruits for other manufacturers.&amp;nbsp; The products of our newly acquired frozen desserts business are produced in Pensacola
 Florida.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our snack products are manufactured at our Phoenix
 Arizona and Bluffton
&amp;nbsp;Indiana plants
 as well as some third-party plants for certain products.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Our fiscal year ends on the last Saturday occurring in the month of December&amp;nbsp;of each calendar year.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Acquisitions and Dispositions&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We account for acquisitions using the acquisition method of accounting.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The results of operations of our acquired businesses have been included in our consolidated results from their respective dates of acquisition.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;On September&amp;nbsp;29
 2014
 we acquired the assets and intellectual property of a small boutique frozen desserts business
 Sin In A Tin
 for approximately $160
000 in cash. An additional amount of up to $0.5 million is payable to the seller in the form of an earn-out based on future net revenues from the Sin In A Tin products (see Note 2).&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;On November&amp;nbsp;8
 2013
 we completed our acquisition of Fresh Frozen Foods
 LLC (&amp;#x201C;Fresh Frozen Foods&amp;#x201D;) for a cash purchase price of $38.4 million plus a working capital adjustment of $0.4 million.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;An additional amount of up to $3.0 million could have been payable to Fresh Frozen Foods as contingent consideration in the form of an earn-out based on 2014 performance (see Note 2).&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;On May&amp;nbsp;28
 2013
 we completed our acquisition of the berry processing business of Willamette Valley Fruit Company
 LLC (&amp;#x201C;Willamette Valley Fruit Company&amp;#x201D;) for a cash purchase price of $9.3 million.&amp;nbsp; An additional amount of up to $3.0 million may be payable to Willamette Valley Fruit Company as contingent consideration in the form of an earn-out if certain performance thresholds are met during the seven-year period following the closing of the transaction (see Note 2).&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;On November&amp;nbsp;5
 2012
 we sold our direct-store-delivery (&amp;#x201C;DSD&amp;#x201D;) business for $1.2 million in cash
 which included a network of independently operated and owned service routes and limited fixed assets associated with the DSD business.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We received an additional $0.3 million as a purchase price adjustment for inventory on-hand.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We recognized a net gain of $1.1 million in continuing operations
 as we will continue to indirectly sell our products through this network at a reduced cost and will no longer sell distributed products.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our sales of distributed products were $2.6 million in fiscal year 2012.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our DSD business was part of our indulgent specialty snack segment and included a limited number of snack food products purchased and sold through our DSD network in Arizona.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Principles of Consolidation&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of Inventure Foods
&amp;nbsp;Inc. and all of its wholly owned subsidiaries.&amp;nbsp; All significant intercompany amounts and transactions have been eliminated.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Our fiscal year ends on the last Saturday occurring in the month of December&amp;nbsp;of each calendar year.&amp;nbsp; Accordingly
 the fiscal year end dates result in an additional week of results every five or six years.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Fiscal year 2014 commenced December&amp;nbsp;29
 2013 and ended December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014
 resulting in a 52-week fiscal year.&amp;nbsp; Fiscal year 2013 commenced December&amp;nbsp;30
 2012 ended December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013
 resulting in a 52-week fiscal year.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Fiscal year 2012 commenced January&amp;nbsp;1
 2012 ended December&amp;nbsp;29
 2012
 resulting in a 52-week fiscal year.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Use of Estimates&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&amp;#x201C;GAAP&amp;#x201D;) requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities
 disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements
 and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period.&amp;nbsp; We routinely evaluate our estimates
 including those related to accruals for customer programs and incentives
 product returns
 bad debts
 income taxes
 long-lived assets
 inventories
 stock-based compensation
 interest rate swap valuations
 accrued broker commissions and contingencies.&amp;nbsp; We base our estimates on historical experience and on various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the circumstances.&amp;nbsp; Actual results could differ from those estimates.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Fair Value of Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability (i.e.
 the &amp;#x201C;exit price&amp;#x201D;) in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;W&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;e classify our investments based upon an established fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The hierarchy gives the highest priority to unadjusted quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities (Level 1 measurement) and the lowest priority to unobservable inputs (Level 3 measurement).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The three levels of the fair value hierarchy are described as follows:&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:28.8pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:36pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:10.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;line-height:106.67%;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;Level 1&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:90.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Unadjusted quoted prices in active markets that are accessible at the measurement date for identical
 unrestricted assets or liabilities.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:10.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;line-height:106.67%;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:90.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:10.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;line-height:106.67%;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;Level 2&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:90.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Quoted prices in markets that are not considered to be active or financial instruments without quoted market prices
 but for which all significant inputs are observable
 either directly or indirectly.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:10.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;line-height:106.67%;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:90.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:10.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;line-height:106.67%;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;&gt;Level 3&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:90.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Prices or valuations that require inputs that are both significant to the fair value measurement and unobservable.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;A financial instrument&amp;#x2019;s level within the fair value hierarchy is based on the lowest level of any input that is significant to the fair value measurement.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:28.8pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;At December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014 and December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013
 the carrying value of cash
 accounts receivable
 accounts payable and accrued liabilities approximate fair values since they are short term in nature.&amp;nbsp; The carrying value of the long-term debt approximates fair value based on the borrowing rates currently available to us for long-term borrowings with similar terms. The following table summarizes the valuation of our assets and liabilities measured at fair value on a recurring basis (in thousands) at the respective dates set forth below:&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;

						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:08.70%;border-top:1pt solid #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;text-align:right;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;#x2014;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.00%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.30%;border-top:1pt solid #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:08.70%;border-top:1pt solid #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;697
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.00%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;

				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.00%;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

053
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.00%;background-color: #CCEEFF;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;

		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Considerable judgment is required in interpreting market data to develop the estimate of fair value of our derivative instruments.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Accordingly
 the estimate may not be indicative of the amounts that we could realize in a current market exchange.&amp;nbsp; The use of different market assumptions or valuation methodologies could have a material effect on the estimated fair value amounts.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The Company&amp;#x2019;s non-qualified deferred compensation plan assets consist of money market and mutual funds invested in domestic and international marketable securities that are directly observable in active markets.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The fair value measurement of the earn-out contingent consideration obligation relates to the acquisitions of Sin In A Tin in September&amp;nbsp;2014
 Willamette Valley Fruit Company in May&amp;nbsp;2013 and Fresh Frozen Foods in November&amp;nbsp;2013
 and is included in accrued liabilities and other long-term liabilities in the consolidated balance sheets.&amp;nbsp; The fair value measurement is based upon significant inputs not observable in the market.&amp;nbsp; Changes in the value of the obligation are recorded as income or expense in our consolidated statements of income.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;To determine the fair value
 we valued the contingent consideration liability based on the expected probability weighted earn-out payments corresponding to the performance thresholds agreed to under the applicable purchase agreements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The expected earn-out payments were then present valued by applying a discount rate that captures a market participants view of the risk associated with the expected earn-out payments.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;During the year ended December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014
 we reduced the value of the contingent consideration related to the Fresh Frozen Foods acquisition to zero due to forecasted reduction in estimated achievement of targets
 and we reduced the value of the contingent consideration related to the Willamette Valley Fruit Company acquisition by $0.3 million based on a reduction in our estimate of the total earn-out expected to be achieved.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;A summary of the activity of the fair value of the measurements using unobservable inputs (Level 3 Liabilities) for the year ended December&amp;nbsp;27
 2014
