				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:11.10%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;text-align:right;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;5.5-6.5&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.08%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:106.67%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The weighted average grant-date fair value of options granted during the years ended December 27
 2014
 December&amp;nbsp;28
 2013 and December 29
 2012 were $5.35
 $3.90 and $3.57
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The expected dividend yield was based on the fact that we have never issued a dividend and have no near term intent to do so.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The volatility assumption was based on historical volatility during the time period that corresponds to the expected life of the option.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The expected life (estimated period of time outstanding) of stock options granted was estimated based on historical exercise activity.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The risk-free interest rate assumption was based on the interest rate of U.S. Treasuries on the date the option was granted.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Prior to May&amp;nbsp;2008
 all stock option grants had a five-year term.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The fair value of these stock option grants is amortized to expense over the service period
 generally five years for employees and one year for members of the Board.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In May&amp;nbsp;2008
 our Board approved a 10-year term for all future stock option grants
 with service periods of five years for employees and one year for members of the Board.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We issue new shares upon the exercise of stock options
 as opposed to reissuing treasury shares.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Preferred Stock&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;We have authorized 50
000 shares preferred stock
 $100 par value (&amp;#x201C;Preferred Stock&amp;#x201D;)
 none of which are outstanding.&amp;nbsp; We may issue such shares of Preferred Stock in the future without stockholder approval.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Subsequent Events&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Subsequent events are events or transactions that occur after the balance sheet date but before financial statements are issued.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We recognize in the financial statements the effects of all subsequent events that provide additional evidence about conditions that existed at the date of the balance sheet
 including the estimates inherent in the process of preparing the financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our financial statements do not recognize subsequent events that provide evidence about conditions that did not exist at the date of the balance sheet but arose after the balance sheet date and before financial statements are filed.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;


		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Accounts Receivable&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;Accounts receivable consist primarily of receivables from customers and distributors for products purchased.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Receivables are generally past due when they are unpaid greater than thirty days.&amp;nbsp; We determine any required reserves by considering a number of factors
 including the length of time the accounts receivable have been outstanding and our loss history.&amp;nbsp; We maintain an allowance for doubtful accounts for estimated losses resulting from the inability of our customers to make required payments.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;&gt;Use of Estimates&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&amp;#x201C;GAAP&amp;#x201D;) requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities
 disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements
 and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period.&amp;nbsp; We routinely evaluate our estimates
 including those related to accruals for customer programs and incentives
 product returns
 bad debts
 income taxes
 long-lived assets
 inventories
 stock-based compensation
 interest rate swap valuations
 accrued broker commissions and contingencies.&amp;nbsp; We base our estimates on historical experience and on various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the circumstances.&amp;nbsp; Actual results could differ from those estimates.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {

							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}

 the FASB issued accounting guidance on the financial statement presentation of an unrecognized tax benefit when a net operating loss carryforward
 a similar tax loss or a tax credit carryforward exists.&nbsp;&nbsp;The guidance is effective prospectively for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those years
 beginning after December&nbsp;15

		

			
		


 the FASB issued amendments to guidance for reporting discontinued operations and disposals of components of an entity.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amended guidance requires that a disposal representing a strategic shift that has (or will have) a major effect on an entity&#x2019;s financial results or a business activity classified as held for sale should be reported as discontinued operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amendments also expand the disclosure requirements for discontinued operations and add new disclosures for individually significant dispositions that do not qualify as discontinued operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amendments are effective prospectively for fiscal years
 and interim reporting periods within those years
 beginning after December&nbsp;15

		

			
		


 the FASB issued new accounting guidance related to revenue recognition.&nbsp;&nbsp;This new standard will replace all current U.S. GAAP guidance on this topic and eliminate all industry-specific guidance.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new revenue recognition standard provides a unified model to determine when and how revenue is recognized.&nbsp;&nbsp;The core principle is that a company should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration for which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance will be effective at the beginning of our 2017 fiscal year and can be applied either retrospectively to each period presented or as a cumulative-effect adjustment as of the date of adoption.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are evaluating the impact
 if any

		

			
		


 the FASB issued new guidance related to stock compensation.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new standard requires that a performance target that affects vesting
 and that could be achieved after the requisite service period
 be treated as a performance condition.&nbsp;&nbsp;As such
 the performance target should not be reflected in estimating the grant date fair value of the award.&nbsp;&nbsp;This update further clarifies that compensation cost should be recognized in the period in which it becomes probable that the performance target will be achieved and should represent the compensation cost attributable to the periods for which the requisite service has already been rendered.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new standard is effective for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those fiscal years
 beginning after December&nbsp;15
 2015 and can be applied either prospectively or retrospectively to all awards outstanding as of the beginning of the earliest annual period presented as an adjustment to opening retained earnings.&nbsp;&nbsp;Early adoption is permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are evaluating the impact
 if any

		

			
		
		
	




        
          

        
          
            
                
              
                
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 acquisition method or combination of entities under common control). This accounting policy may include a general discussion of the purchase method or acquisition method of accounting (including for example
 the treatment accorded contingent consideration
 the identification of assets and liabilities
 the purchase price allocation process
 how the fair values of acquired assets and liabilities are determined) and the entity's specific application thereof. An entity that acquires another entity in a leveraged buyout transaction generally discloses the accounting policy followed by the acquiring entity in determining the basis used to value its interest in the acquired entity
 and the rationale for that accounting policy.
              
                
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 including the policy for determining which items are treated as cash equivalents. Other information that may be disclosed includes (1) the nature of any restrictions on the entity's use of its cash and cash equivalents
 (2) whether the entity's cash and cash equivalents are insured or expose the entity to credit risk
 (3) the classification of any negative balance accounts (overdrafts)
 and (4) the carrying basis of cash equivalents (for example

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}

 2014
 we acquired the assets and intellectual property of a small boutique frozen desserts business
 Sin In A Tin
 for approximately $160
000 in cash. An additional amount of up to $0.5 million is payable to the seller in the form of an earn-out based on future net revenues from the Sin In A Tin products.&nbsp;&nbsp;At the time of acquisition
 the contingent consideration was recorded at $0.2 million based on the fair value assessment.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally
 we recorded $0.1 million of identifiable intangible assets and $0.1 million of net tangible assets that were assumed as a part of this acquisition based on their estimated fair values

		

			
		



		

			
		

			
		

			
		


 2013
 we acquired substantially all of the assets
 properties and rights of Fresh Frozen Foods
 a branded frozen vegetable processor.&nbsp;&nbsp;As consideration for the acquisition
 we assumed certain liabilities and obligations of Fresh Frozen Foods and paid an aggregate purchase price of $38.4 million in cash plus a working capital adjustment of $0.4 million.&nbsp;&nbsp;A portion of the purchase price was used to settle Fresh Frozen Foods&#x2019; existing debt as of the closing of the transaction.&nbsp;&nbsp;An additional amount of up to $3.0 million could have been payable to Fresh Frozen Foods as contingent consideration in the form of an earn-out based on 2014 performance.&nbsp;&nbsp;At the time of acquisition
 the contingent consideration was recorded at $2.7 million based on the fair value assessment at acquisition.&nbsp;&nbsp;Such contingent payment
 if any
 would be paid during the first quarter of 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Acquisition costs of $1.1 million were incurred during the year ended December&nbsp;28
 2013 and are included within selling
 general and administrative expenses.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amount of net revenues attributable to Fresh Frozen Foods included in the consolidated statements of operations since the acquisition date were $8.9 million in fiscal 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not allocate certain selling

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}

 in accordance with relevant authoritative guidance.&nbsp;&nbsp;If the undiscounted future cash flows are less than the carrying value of the asset or group of assets being evaluated

 we recognize operating revenues upon shipment of products to customers

 promotional allowances
 coupon redemption and discounts are also recorded as a reduction of revenues in our consolidated financial statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;These allowances are estimated based on a percentage of sales returns using historical and current market information.&nbsp;&nbsp;We record certain reductions to revenue for promotional allowances.&nbsp;&nbsp;There are several types of promotional allowances
 such as off-invoice allowances
 rebates and shelf space allowances.&nbsp;&nbsp;An off-invoice allowance is a reduction of the sales price that is directly deducted from the invoice amount.&nbsp;&nbsp;We record the amount of the deduction as a reduction to revenue when the transaction occurs.&nbsp;&nbsp;We record certain allowances for coupon redemptions
 scan-back promotions and other promotional activities as a reduction to revenue.&nbsp;&nbsp;Anytime we offer consideration (cash or credit) as a trade advertising or promotional allowance to a purchaser of products at any point along the distribution chain

 the FASB issued accounting guidance on the financial statement presentation of an unrecognized tax benefit when a net operating loss carryforward
 a similar tax loss or a tax credit carryforward exists.&nbsp;&nbsp;The guidance is effective prospectively for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those years
 beginning after December&nbsp;15

		

			
		


 the FASB issued amendments to guidance for reporting discontinued operations and disposals of components of an entity.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amended guidance requires that a disposal representing a strategic shift that has (or will have) a major effect on an entity&#x2019;s financial results or a business activity classified as held for sale should be reported as discontinued operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amendments also expand the disclosure requirements for discontinued operations and add new disclosures for individually significant dispositions that do not qualify as discontinued operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amendments are effective prospectively for fiscal years
 and interim reporting periods within those years
 beginning after December&nbsp;15

		

			
		


 the FASB issued new accounting guidance related to revenue recognition.&nbsp;&nbsp;This new standard will replace all current U.S. GAAP guidance on this topic and eliminate all industry-specific guidance.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new revenue recognition standard provides a unified model to determine when and how revenue is recognized.&nbsp;&nbsp;The core principle is that a company should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration for which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance will be effective at the beginning of our 2017 fiscal year and can be applied either retrospectively to each period presented or as a cumulative-effect adjustment as of the date of adoption.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are evaluating the impact
 if any

		

			
		


 the FASB issued new guidance related to stock compensation.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new standard requires that a performance target that affects vesting
 and that could be achieved after the requisite service period
 be treated as a performance condition.&nbsp;&nbsp;As such
 the performance target should not be reflected in estimating the grant date fair value of the award.&nbsp;&nbsp;This update further clarifies that compensation cost should be recognized in the period in which it becomes probable that the performance target will be achieved and should represent the compensation cost attributable to the periods for which the requisite service has already been rendered.&nbsp;&nbsp;The new standard is effective for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those fiscal years
 beginning after December&nbsp;15
 2015 and can be applied either prospectively or retrospectively to all awards outstanding as of the beginning of the earliest annual period presented as an adjustment to opening retained earnings.&nbsp;&nbsp;Early adoption is permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are evaluating the impact
 if any

		

			
		
		
	




        
          

        
          
            

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 consolidation and basis of presentation of financial statements disclosure
 and significant accounting policies of the reporting entity. May be provided in more than one note to the financial statements
 as long as users are provided with an understanding of (1) the significant judgments and assumptions made by an enterprise in determining whether it must consolidate a VIE and/or disclose information about its involvement with a VIE
 (2) the nature of restrictions on a consolidated VIE's assets reported by an enterprise in its statement of financial position
 including the carrying amounts of such assets
 (3) the nature of
 and changes in
 the risks associated with an enterprise's involvement with the VIE
 and (4) how an enterprise's involvement with the VIE affects the enterprise's financial position
 financial performance
 and cash flows.  Describes procedure if disclosures are provided in more than one note to the financial statements.

var Show = {};
Show.LastAR = null
Show.hideAR = function(){
	Show.LastAR.style.display = 'none';
};
Show.showAR = function ( link
 id
 win ){
	if( Show.LastAR ){
		Show.hideAR();
	}
	var ref = link;
	do {
		ref = ref.nextSibling;
	} while (ref && ref.nodeName != 'TABLE');
	if (!ref || ref.nodeName != 'TABLE') {
		var tmp = win ?
			win.document.getElementById(id) :
			document.getElementById(id);
		if( tmp ){
			ref = tmp.cloneNode(true);
			ref.id = '';
			link.parentNode.appendChild(ref);
		}
	}
	if( ref ){
		ref.style.display = 'block';
		Show.LastAR = ref;
	}
};
Show.toggleNext = function( link ){
	var ref = link;
	do{
		ref = ref.nextSibling;
	}while( ref.nodeName != 'DIV' );
	if( ref.style &&
		ref.style.display &&
		ref.style.display == 'none' ){
		ref.style.display = 'block';
		if( link.textContent ){
			link.textContent = link.textContent.replace( '+'
 '-' );
		}else{
			link.innerText = link.innerText.replace( '+'
 '-' );
		}
	}else{
		ref.style.display = 'none';
		if( link.textContent ){
			link.textContent = link.textContent.replace( '-'
 '+' );
		}else{
			link.innerText = link.innerText.replace( '-'
 '+' );
		}
	}
};











    
    
							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}

 Matter.&nbsp;&nbsp;While we currently believe the &#x201C;all natural&#x201D; statement on the smoothie kits are not misleading and in full compliance with FDA guidelines
 Matter
 and intend to vigorously defend against them.&nbsp;&nbsp;On September&nbsp;17
 2013
 we filed a motion to dismiss
 seeking to dismiss plaintiffs&#x2019; claims as to gelatin and the Orange Dream Machine smoothie kit.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our motion was denied in November&nbsp;2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On February&nbsp;3
 2014
 the plaintiffs filed a motion to certify a class of all persons in California who bought certain Jamba Juice smoothie kits.&nbsp;&nbsp;On September&nbsp;18
 2014
 the court issued an order granting class certification solely for purposes of determining liability and denying certification for purposes of damages.&nbsp;&nbsp;The court requested further briefing on the question of whether it has jurisdiction to certify a class for purposes of granting injunctive relief.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Following mediation
 the basic terms of a proposed class settlement were reached.&nbsp;&nbsp;The parties signed a definitive agreement that was filed with the court for approval on December 1
 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;The court&#x2019;s ruling on a motion for preliminary approval is pending and will be followed by a subsequent final approval hearing.&nbsp;&nbsp;If approved by the court
 a settlement class will be certified for injunctive relief only
 requiring the Company to (i) remove the &#x201C;all natural&#x201D; designation on the labels of the challenged products and (ii) pay $5
000 to each of the two individual plaintiffs and up to $425
000 to plaintiffs&#x2019; counsel for fees and costs. The case would also be dismissed and the Company would pay no damages to class members

		

			
		


 2014

&nbsp;Inc. doing business as Boulder Canyon Natural Foods

 officers and members of our board of directors (the &#x201C;Board&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;Restricted stock awards and restricted stock units granted to members of the Board are granted with a one-year service period.&nbsp;&nbsp;Restricted stock awards and restricted stock units granted to the Company&#x2019;s officers vest over three years and typically contain performance restrictions that are required to be achieved over a three year measurement period in order for the shares to be released.&nbsp;&nbsp;The number of performance-based restricted stock ultimately released varies based on whether we achieve certain financial results.&nbsp;&nbsp;Restricted stock units granted to non-officer employees generally vest over three or five years.&nbsp;&nbsp;We record compensation expense each period based on the market price of our Common Stock at the time of grant and
 for performance-based restricted stock awards and units
 our estimate of the most probable number of shares that will ultimately be released.&nbsp;&nbsp;The related stock-based compensation expense is included in selling
 general and administrative expenses.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally
 the compensation expense is adjusted for our estimate of forfeitures.&nbsp;&nbsp;Recipients of restricted Common Stock are entitled to receive any dividends declared on our Common Stock and have voting rights

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}

							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
